          "body": "The chapter's verdict (1:24-31) is two-edged. To those who consent and obey (1:19), refining produces restoration — *I will restore your judges as at the first, and your counselors as at the beginning; after that you will be called the city of righteousness, a faithful city* (1:26). The end-state is recovery of original calling. To those who refuse and rebel (1:20), the same fire that refines the responsive consumes the resistant — *the strong man will become tinder... they shall both burn together* (1:31). The chapter ends with both outcomes side by side. Zion is redeemed *with justice* (1:27) — not despite God's justice but through it. The whole book of Isaiah unfolds how this is possible: the Suffering Servant of Isaiah 53 bears the sin so that Zion can be redeemed with justice rather than at justice's expense."
